Hmm.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Am I okay?

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Yeah.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:11.000
President's fine.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Huh?

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
You're good.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Magnificent.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Yeah, yeah, but I want to make sure.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
I don't want, because she's the first one who's going to tell me where,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:31.000
you couldn't get somebody to just do that, or fix that, or drag that, or.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Hmm.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:33.000
Yeah.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:42.000
We'll go start there, if you give us an introduction to yourself, please.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Yes.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Ready?

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Okay.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
My name is Roy Grant.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:56.000
I was born in Jamaica and came to the United Kingdom at the age of 19 years of age.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:07.000
I had a wonderful childhood marred by affliction, but of a good, good parentage.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:13.000
My parents sent me here to the United Kingdom at the age of 19,

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:21.000
because after leaving school, I loved to do engineering, and I began my engineering apprenticeship.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Arriving in this country, oh my goodness, what a change.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
And so much, so different from what I'm used to.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Cold wind, my hands, my fingers numbed, my body shivers.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:47.000
And I arrived in Southampton by a ship called the SSB Gona, 11 days a night aboard the ship,

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
which wasn't a very nice experience.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:59.000
But when I arrived at Southampton, we got on a train to Victoria, and then from Victoria,

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:06.000
I went to Birmingham and there to live with my cousin.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:16.000
I spent the first week getting used to the family I now become, to adopt,

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:24.000
and the home that is going to be my own for no, well, in fact,

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:33.000
on my application to come to this country, I had to put on it, I'll be here for five years.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So, at that point, I would have been, all my intention that I was going to spend five years in the country,

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.000
and then I'll be going back to Jamaica.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:51.000
However, I had the first week to get used to the place as it were,

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:58.000
and the family that was about to adopt me as their own.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:09.000
And after a week, I was taken to what they call the labour exchange in those days,

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:17.000
which is the employment department, the job centre, which is now known as,

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:21.000
and sign on for a job.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:30.000
And at the same time, I was purchasing the evening news to see what vacancies were available.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Anyway, between these two outlets, I saw quite a number of vacancies for apprentices for engineering,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
and I thought, this is great, I wouldn't have a problem here.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:55.000
However, I would send for applications, and applications would come along,

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.000
but in them days, the post was pretty good.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:10.000
And furthermore, in some of these notices for engineers, there used to be a little write in there,

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:20.000
which you fill in, and you get through to the engineer works that you seek out very quickly.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Anyway, when I received some sort of confirmation that my request was being looked at,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:40.000
and I fill in these applications, send them back, they would quickly send to me and say,

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:42.000
well, come in for an interview.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:57.000
And this is the strangest thing is, when I remember speaking to one or two people at this job,

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:09.000
at the works, and they were so enthusiastic about me, because my English wasn't any different from what it is now.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:18.000
So they wouldn't realize that I was black, and it was just a matter of Bromie English,

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.000
because it's not really straight English in many places.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And they say, come in. But when I got there, and two words, you know, where do you live? I said.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:44.000
How long have you been in the country? I said, well, a month.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And then they say, well, who did you learn your engineering with? I say, in Jamaica.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:59.000
I say, well, I'm sorry, but we can't have you because you have a broken apprenticeship.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:05.000
And I was turned down, dreadful.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:14.000
And this repeat itself on several occasions. So I was really fed up.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:20.000
In fact, what is the worst thing about this discriminative attitude?

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:31.000
I remember going to the door of a few engineering places, and in those days, they had a window like a hatchet.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:37.000
And like a hatchet, you slide this hatchet door open, and the receptionist or whoever it is speak to you.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:46.000
And I remember walking up to the door, and the door was in a position where you could see the hatchet window.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:53.000
And I could see the lady sitting at the desk looking out through the hatchet window to see who was coming through the door.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:01.000
And as soon as she sees me, the hatchet went, clunk, shuts tight.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:09.000
And she walked away and shut the door behind her in her room because they didn't want any black people.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:26.000
It later come to my knowledge that, you see, engineering or precision engineering in the 60s were the rose-roised trade for the poor man,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:33.000
those who couldn't send their kids to university or who didn't pass the 11 plus.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:38.000
And for a black man to take those spaces was very rare.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:54.000
Furthermore, the workers or the tradesmen who have a boy child who would want to continue being an engineer would put their names down,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:02.000
just like they used to do in the schools, would put their names on as a child so that when they leave school, they go straight into that engineering work.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:09.000
So you have father, grandfather, grandchildren, all family in that engineering.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:26.000
Well, I was so fed up that I wrote to my cousin who lived in Wales, and I told her what the situation was,

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:35.000
and, you know, it's discrimination and nobody wants to give me a job because I wasn't intent to do anything else.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And she said, no, as far as she's concerned, people in Wales are very, very nice, they're very cooperative and so on.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
So come down. And I came to Wales.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
How old were you?

00:08:52.000 --> 00:09:09.000
When I came to Wales, I came to Wales on the, yes, I came to Wales, I can remember now, the last week in July, 1962, and just on my 20th birthday.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:24.000
And it was what they call the two weeks shut down holiday, the summer holidays.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And the newspaper came out, which was the, I can't remember if it's the Echo or the August, came out or the early August,

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:41.000
and I read it and it says, engineer apprentice wanted.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And I didn't stop to think, I just, and there was a telephone number, and I picked up and I rang.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:57.000
And this gentleman said to me, yes, we want an apprentice, we want apprentices, you know, if you want to come along.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:06.000
I went and I saw the form and because at this engineering work, which was grinding engineering,

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:14.000
and he said to me, yes, but I can't give you the yes today.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:21.000
You have to come back a following week and see the owner and they will give you yes.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.000
Well, I went back the following week and you wouldn't believe it.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:32.000
I was on top form because they said yes, I, they would take me on.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
I was so pleased.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:46.000
And that was the beginning of my future as an engineering, position engineering apprenticeship in Wales.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:52.000
So I am grateful to come into Wales because I succeed in doing what I set out to do.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:01.000
Now you have been working in engineering, you have grown up.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:09.000
When did your wife or your fiance come over?

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:19.000
Well, in those early days, what the government, the government was stopping everyone from coming.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:25.000
But if you have dependent relatives or your fiance, they could come.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:36.000
However, for fiancees, fiancees could come with one premises that you have to get married within three months of arriving in the country.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:46.000
And so it wasn't long before I put everything I could together to send for my fiance.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:53.000
And the following year in 1963, she came and we got married in December of that year.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:12:05.000
Well, it wasn't long after we made our life together and we ended up having four kids, wonderful children.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:14.000
One girl and three boys, well, plus one other boy, make five kids.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:26.000
And yes, however, I don't know if this interview is the right place to do it, but I have to tell you this.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:42.000
Whenever everyone who succeeds, every black person who came here during the 60s and succeed in doing anything that is very important,

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:47.000
they have to sacrifice something.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:13:04.000
And unfortunately, my family, unwittingly, I sacrificed my family to develop my engineering skill because I have to work twice as hard as the white man.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:22.000
And I had to be twice as clever as the white man because within a short time, the introduction of nylon to the manufacturing industry, especially textile,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:28.000
create the need for wrapping cutting tools.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:38.000
And I was the man who was rushed to develop that wrapping cutting tool in tungsten carbide,

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:44.000
which makes the company and a lot of other people very rich.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:58.000
But I was a nobody to the English. I was black. I wasn't rich.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:20.000
Furthermore, I have no right to say, to have any say in the development as what would I think in saying I could take ownership of the fact that this is what I've done as evidence.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:29.000
No, everything was pointed out to the ownership of the owner of that engineering.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:47.000
So I can only say it with conviction that I've done it, but I cannot embrace a certificate to say, well, this is what I have done and I can be and I am satisfied that I've been compensated.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:15:03.000
No, but I feel good because engineering is what I love and I have done it so no one can take that away from me.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
When you say Wales, where are you?

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:21.000
Wales, well, I say that I talk about Birmingham carries a lot of treated me with resentment and discrimination.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:28.000
It doesn't mean to say that there is not there wasn't discrimination and resentment in Wales.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:40.000
There was, but it was undermined a lot different from in Birmingham.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:46.000
Birmingham, it was on the doorstep. In Wales, it's under the carpet.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:16:10.000
And the different was a subtlety because, for instance, during my engineering work and I was developing this stuff so rapidly and to compensate me and to keep me within that work environment so that I wouldn't be poached or go anywhere else.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:20.000
I was rapidly promoted from charging to foreman to production manager.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:31.000
And I remember, you know, one of the men who made friends with me and he was the one who gave me the first cup of tea.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:41.000
And he said, he went to the, this is what the foreman told me after the event.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:59.000
And he apparently he told the foreman, he went to the foreman and asked the foreman if this black bastard come to give me authority, a job or what should I do?

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:06.000
And the foreman was looked at him and this is what and I quote what they are saying.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:14.000
The foreman said, when I give you a job to do, what do you do?

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:23.000
And he answered, he carried it out. So he said, you know that I'm a Polish man.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:30.000
He said, yes. So the foreman answered and said, well, what is the difference?

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:38.000
And the strangest thing is I did not know anything about this that went on.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:52.000
It was only when the foreman then took me in his confident and advised me to be very careful and to be very straight with everyone.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:59.000
Don't give anyone the right, the chance to build up any resentment against me.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:14.000
And he start to share out all these things that might affect me, might affect my project, my progress, you know, in becoming a good boss as it were then.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:17.000
When was then the next turning point?

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:23.000
The next turning point is I reached a production manager.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:32.000
I've been having to and this is the this is this is the underline of the discrimination comes in.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:41.000
They brought in five different other people to take on the job that I have been doing.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:50.000
In other words, to to manage me in the work and set them up as production manager.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:58.000
And then I had to teach those guys what to tell me what to do.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:07.000
It was ridiculous. So after a time, I just got fed up and I said, well, I'm changing my arm.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:20.000
I'm changing from engineering and I went into into taxi proprietary and I was a taxi proprietor for over five years.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:25.000
And and, you know, it was very successful.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:45.000
But there again, to make it successful, I sacrifice a lot of time building it because I was black and no one wants to to call a black taxi man to take their their daughter to church on the way for their wedding and all like that or to take them out when they're properly dressed.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:50.000
No one wants a black man to drive them or.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:54.000
And it takes a while to build up the business.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:20:05.000
And do you and during that time, I sometime have neglected my children because when they want me to take them to sports and so on.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:12.000
So I was busy working to, you know, and helping somebody else or something like that.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:21.000
So I have I have a lot of regret in the fact that I did not.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.000
I did not equate the important.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:27.000
And this is what I'm telling you guys.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:45.000
No matter how much you want something, when you have a family, try to mesh what you're doing that is equally divided between what you want and what your family is required of you.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:49.000
Because it can come back to bite you on the ass.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:57.000
And I'm not saying my kids resent me now, but they could, you know.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:04.000
They they they it's hard to forget.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:09.000
You know, I was speaking about the blindness.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.000
Yeah.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:15.000
Well, I've been being a taxi propriety.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:22.000
It wasn't long after, you know, people take advantage and they smashing up the vehicle left, right and center.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:32.000
And I decided to take a change and that change led me into into.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:36.000
Develop catering a mobile catering business.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:42.000
And this mobile catering business was was supplying.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:53.000
Break break meals, break snacks for the workers, because in those days is very few.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:22:01.000
Companies, manufacturers have a canteen whereby, you know, people could go into and.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
And get something to eat.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.000
They would have to send someone to up to the shop.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:15.000
So it's a it's all, you know, the company would be we would be losing at least three quarter of an hour for the person to go to the shop.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.000
At least three quarters of an hour every day.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:21.000
It's a lot of time over the week.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:29.000
And I was going in and I was taking in all these snacks for these people so that they could stay within the workplace and have their snacks and so on.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:33.000
And that went on for a few years and I was very successful at it.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:36.000
However, like.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:44.000
The overall of over 20 years of of hard work and and.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:48.000
Stress.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:51.000
Create diabetes.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:55.000
And the diabetes.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:23:07.000
Become so great taking over my body so much that it caused hemorrhage in my right eye and rendered me blind.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:11.000
Completely blind. Oh, you heard me say my right eye.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:17.000
So what about my left eye? Well, like I said in the beginning.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:21.000
I had a good childhood, but it was flawed.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:27.000
And that's when I was two years of age, I lost sight to an accident in my left eye.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:36.000
So I only had one eye, even though I was insistent on being an engineer and was successful at it.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:44.000
So diabetes cause hemorrhage on the optic nerves in my right eye.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:47.000
And I was completely blind.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:53.000
And my my mobile catering business went.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:58.000
I could no longer drive.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:01.000
And I lost my license.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:05.000
I lost my business and.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:09.000
I lost my head because the shock.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:13.000
Look at me and he explained something to you.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:17.000
I just I just finished having my Sunday dinner.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:24.000
And we sat at the dinner table and we were all happy having a laugh and a joke.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:29.000
And I pick up my pipe because we smoke a pipe.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:31.000
I smoke a pipe by then.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:36.000
I clean the pipe and in them days, you know, you smoke in the house, you smoke around the table.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:40.000
And and I clean my pipe.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:48.000
And no before I could fill my pipe and bend in my head like this, cleaning it out.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:59.000
It's as though I'm looking at a piece of glass like this and somebody drop a tip of well, I didn't know it was blood.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:01.000
Something red.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:07.000
And it was just flowing over this piece of glass.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:13.000
And it flows and until all I could see was.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:20.000
Blaring light around the square ends of this glass.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:26.000
And that was it. So I ran in the bathroom, washed my face and all that.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:29.000
And there's nothing happening.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:31.000
I was so shocked. I don't know.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:34.000
How the hell did I get into the bathroom and I couldn't see? I was blind.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
How did I get there?

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:42.000
But I got there to the bathroom, washed my face and nobody will my aunt.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:46.000
Until this day, I can't tell you how I got there.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:53.000
Well, the trauma and that's where the trauma began because I went to the hospital and there was no one there to tell me.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:58.000
How am I going to see again or if I will ever see again or they can do anything.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
So I was sent home.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:03.000
The following day I went back.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:04.000
Same thing.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:11.000
And it took three days until the specialist came back from where all the day where he were.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:15.000
And he came back and then they begin to panic.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:23.000
And start to phone up all the different hospitals to find out who was the best person to clean.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:32.000
To take away this sort of mushroom thing that left on the optic nerves from the bleeding.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:45.000
Anyway, it took I think about three weeks or so for the hospital to make an appointment when for this procedure to take place.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:48.000
And it did take place.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:59.000
And the first time I went and they done it, which was Moorfield in London.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:02.000
It didn't work.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:05.000
So disappointed.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:06.000
It didn't work.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:15.000
It took another six weeks for them to do this surgery again, once again.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:23.000
And that time this time, the minute they took away the bandage and off my eye.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:30.000
What I can only describe as pink balloon, pink jelly.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:37.000
I was looking through a glass of pink jelly.

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:52.000
And from there on, my sight began to get stronger and stronger.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:28:01.000
And you know, I was discharged and went home.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:08.000
However, I couldn't remember how to pronounce a word.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:14.000
My brain, I was like, I couldn't write, I couldn't do nothing.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:16.000
I couldn't remember things.

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:20.000
